At this point I will turn for a moment to the parallel episode in the poem of Silius Italicus. Silius was not a great poet, but one might fancy that he had a good opportunity in the gathering of Italian contingents to repel Hannibal. Unluckily there were too many of them, and the conscientious verse-maker‚ modelling his work on Homer’s catalogue rather than on Virgil's pageant, overdoes his detail, hewilclers and wearies his reader, without arousing any keen sense of national exultation.1 His flashlight is a feeble one; the endless procession passes‚ and we grow stupid and weary. We cannot see the wood for the trees: towns, rivers, mountains, gods and temples‚ soldiers and their armour, pass before us without making us the least enthusiastic, and I think that even the Italian of the early empire could hardly have been moved to emotion.
